'''Amir Ansari''' ({{lang-fa|امیر انصاری}}) is an American Chief Technology Officer and Co-Founder of [[Prodea Systems]].

Along with his sister-in-law [[Anousheh Ansari]], he made a multimillion-dollar contribution to the [[Ansari X Prize]] foundation on May 5, 2004, the 43rd anniversary of [[Alan Shepard]]'s sub-orbital spaceflight. The X Prize was officially renamed the ''Ansari X Prize'' in honour of their donation.

Born in 1970 in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]], Ansari immigrated to the United States before the [[Iranian Revolution]]. He received his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in electrical engineering and computer science at [[George Mason University]]. Amir, along with his brother Hamid and sister-in-law [[Anousheh Ansari]], founded [[Telecom Technologies, Inc.]] (TTI) in 1993, and served as the company's [[Chief technical officer|CTO]]. TTI was acquired by [[Sonus Networks, Inc.]] in January 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investors.sonusnet.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=912057-01-3972&CIK=1105472 |title=Form 8-K current report / Sonus Networks, Inc. / Item 2. Acquisition or Disposition of Assets |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |date=2001-02-02 |accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>

Prodea has announced the formation of a partnership with [[Space Adventures]], Ltd. and the [[Russian Federal Space Agency|Federal Space Agency of the Russian Federation]] (FSA) to create a fleet of suborbital spaceflight vehicles for global commercial use.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}

